04622nam a22006375i 9780231553902DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021002487  a97802315539027 a10.7312/maju201042doi  a(DE-B1597)612560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1993.5.I8bM346 2022 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aMajumdar, Rochona, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt Cinema and India’s Forgotten Futures :bFilm and History in the Postcolony /cRochona Majumdar. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b35 b&w film stills  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: THE HISTORY OF ART CINEMA -- t1. Art Cinema: The Indian Career of a Global Category -- t2. The “New” Indian Cinema: Journeys of the Art Film -- t3. Debating Radical Cinema: A History of the Film Society Movement -- tPART II: ART FILMS AS HISTORY -- t4. Ritwik Ghatak and the Overcoming of History -- t5. “Anger and After”: History, Political Cinema, and Mrinal Sen -- t6. The Untimely Filmmaker: Ray’s City Trilogy and a Crisis of Historicism -- tEpilogue: Art Cinema and Our Present -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe project of Indian art cinema began in the years following independence in 1947, at once evoking the global reach of the term “art film” and speaking to the aspirations of the new nation-state. In this pioneering book, Rochona Majumdar examines key works of Indian art cinema to demonstrate how film emerged as a mode of doing history and that, in so doing, it anticipated some of the most influential insights of postcolonial thought.Majumdar details how filmmakers as well as a host of film societies and publications sought to foster a new cinematic culture for the new nation, fueled by enthusiasm for a future of progress and development. Good films would help make good citizens: art cinema would not only earn global prestige but also shape discerning individuals capable of exercising aesthetic and political judgment. During the 1960s, however, Satyajit Ray, Mrinal Sen, and Ritwik Ghatak—the leading figures of Indian art cinema—became disillusioned with the belief that film was integral to national development. Instead, Majumdar contends, their works captured the unresolvable contradictions of the postcolonial present, which pointed toward possible, yet unrealized futures.Analyzing the films of Ray, Sen, and Ghatak, and working through previously unexplored archives of film society publications, Majumdar offers a radical reinterpretation of Indian film history. Art Cinema and India’s Forgotten Futures offers sweeping new insights into film’s relationship with the postcolonial condition and its role in decolonial imaginations of the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszIndia. 0aMotion pictureszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew wave filmszIndiaxHistory and criticism. 0aPostcolonialism in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553902/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK